            "last_activity_date": 1503200424,
            "creation_date": 1503198187,
            "body": "<blockquote>\n  <p>Why is it fundamental for the module system to know uses of a particular service ...<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>Because of dependency resolution.  <a href=\"http://openjdk.java.net/projects/jigsaw/spec/sotms/\" rel=\"noreferrer\"><em>The State of the Module System<\/em><\/a> says in the example a few lines above your quoted text:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>In order for the <code>java.sql<\/code> module to make use of this driver, the <code>ServiceLoader<\/code> class must be able to instantiate the driver class via reflection; for that to happen, the module system must add the driver module to the module graph and resolve its dependencies ...<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>The key point is that reflection is used to do the instantiation.  It happens <em>after<\/em> module resolution ... and after the application has started running.<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>... especially how will this introduce efficiency?<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>Scanning a codebase for all calls to <code>ServiceLoader::load<\/code> is expensive.  It is not sufficient to just know that a method is called (which could be done by analysis of classfile dependencies).  You also need to know what <em>parameters were used<\/em> to determine what classes are going to be loaded.  And (as the SotMS document points out) that would be open to errors; e.g. if the parameters are runtime expressions rather than compile-time constant expressions.<\/p>\n\n<p>The solution they have adopted is to provide a way to explicitly declare a dependency on a reflectively loaded class.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 45778058,
            "question_id": 45777949,
            "last_edit_date": 1503200424
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/s4qlq.png?s=256",
                "account_id": 6780825,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 5221149,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/5221149/andreas",
                "reputation": 160084,
                "display_name": "Andreas"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 6,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1503198105,
            "creation_date": 1503198105,
            "body": "<p>Quoting from Java 9 javadoc of <a href=\"http://download.java.net/java/jdk9/docs/api/java/util/ServiceLoader.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\"><code>ServiceLoader<\/code><\/a> (emphasis added by me):<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>An application obtains a service loader for a given service by invoking one of the static <code>load<\/code> methods of ServiceLoader. If the application is a module, then its module declaration must have a <em>uses<\/em> directive that specifies the service; <strong>this helps to locate providers and ensure they will execute reliably<\/strong>. In addition, if the service is not in the application module, then the module declaration must have a <em>requires<\/em> directive that specifies the module which exports the service.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n",
            "answer_id": 45778052,
            "question_id": 45777949
        }
